@@rThe Sealed Warrants@@N

@@dAt the center of institutional history lie the records that no city wishes
to open.@@N

@@yDuring the Ash-and-Iron Decades, Midgaard's magistrates issued sealed
warrants condemning debtors, petty criminals, and 'unregistered persons' to
labor service. The Violet Compact's registry apparatus processed these
individuals as 'arcane material' rather than citizens, stripping them of
civic identity. The Spirebound Conclave received these subjects for
experimentation: the crystal-binding research, the sentinel forging, the
spirit imprinting.@@N

@@eMidgaard's trade ledger contains a single surviving line item: payment of
'forty iron bars and six condemned debtors' to 'the mountain academy' in
exchange for 'consultation on defensive ward design.' The entry is
unremarkable in context. Condemned prisoners were routine currency in
frontier-era trade.@@N

@@dKowloon's Black Ledger, if it exists, contains the corresponding entries
from the delta settlements. Courier Lantern Office runners whisper that the
list of mountain expeditions that never returned is longer than any official
would admit, and that several entries bear jade seals of Kowloon's own
Magistracy.@@N

@@rThe Conclave's own experiment records survive in the Sunken Sanctum's
sealed vaults: forced induction logs, coercive intake records, and the
progression from scholarly archive to institutional horror.@@N

@@yThe Violet Eclipse Cathedral processed the transit warrants. Its quarantine
chambers held condemned persons in transit. When the cathedral withdrew into
eclipse, it took its copy of the transit ledgers: records that Midgaard's
Reckoning Faction has sought for generations.@@N

@@eBoth cities know what they did. Both chose not to say. Midgaard's Reckoning
faction seeks exposure while its Continuity faction seeks burial. Kowloon's
parallel factions mirror this divide. Neither city can prosecute the other's
reformers without opening its own archive.@@N

@@dKiess's founding charter explicitly repudiates sealed-warrant governance,
written as a direct response to Evermeet's participation in the transfer
apparatus. The clause forbidding any predecessor authority's sealed warrant
from binding a Kiess citizen was written so this could never happen again.@@N
